{"questionId":"27791","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><strong>In this question you will investigate curved surface areas and use calculus to derive key formulae used in geometry.</strong></p>\n<p><br>Consider the straight line from the origin, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>m</mi><mi>x</mi></math>, where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>≤</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>≤</mo><mi>h</mi></math> and m, h are positive constants.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/e60412f42db3f083e19ebe655fcb3de165ee5fac.png\"></p>\n<p>When this line is rotated through <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>360</mn><mo>°</mo></math> about the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>-axis, a cone is formed with a curved surface area <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi></math> given by:</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><munderover><mo>∫</mo><mn>0</mn><mi>h</mi></munderover><mi>y</mi><msqrt><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>m</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt><mo>d</mo><mi>x</mi></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Now consider the general case where a cone is formed by rotating the line <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>m</mi><mi>x</mi></math> where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>≤</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>≤</mo><mi>h</mi></math> through <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>360</mn><mo>°</mo></math> about the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>-axis.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Deduce an expression for the slant height <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>l</mi></math> in terms of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>l</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><msup><mi>h</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>l</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><msup><mi>h</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>h</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi>m</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mi>h</mi><msqrt><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>m</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"27791","referenceCode":"22N.3.AHL.TZ0.2b.ii","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Deduce an expression for the slant height l in terms of h and m.","paper":"3","level":"HL","questionNumber":"b.ii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.3—Applications: angles of elevation and depression, bearings"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}